meta.microhabitat: Sifted leaf litter sample. GIS 1800,900. All swampy, litter thin, much of it sam
meta.collectionnotes: NOTEBY J.Longino: Sifted leaf litter sample. GIS 1800,900. All swampy, litter thin, much of it sampled from suspended accumulations on logs, in small palms. Litter wet and gummy. [fuller site description in original field notes]. I took separate samples off on days 1,2,4. The day-1 sample had 24 species. The day-2 sample had one additional species, the big blue-black shiny Hypoponera queen. The day 4 sample contained one additional species, Lachnomyrmex.

meta.microhabitat: leaf litter sample, GIS 1800/900. [examples of each ant species, all parasitica
meta.collectionnotes: NOTEBY J.Longino: leaf litter sample, GIS 1800/900. [examples of each ant species, all parasitica extracted]. I continued the beta diversity project. I changed the methods as follows: Taking sample: In a straight line (transect), walk five paces, take one hopper full (subjectively taking whatever litter looks good) (a hopper full is between one half and three quarters full, usually). Repeat until 10 hoppers have been sifted. Orientation of sampling transect: always 123 degrees from GIS pole. For the repeat samples around GIS 1800/900, continually move south (213 degrees), five to 10 paces each time, go east (123 degrees) until the juncture of swamp and slope is reached, then do transect up the slope, continuing at 123 degrees. Length of time in hanging sacks: 3 days. Today's samples: 2000/900 sample taken at about 1000hrs; 1800/900 sample taken at 1200hrs. The day was sunny with no rain. The litter was uniformly moist. The samples were hung by 1400hrs. Each sample filled about 2.5 hanging sacks. [samples taken off 5 Jul, 1400-1600hrs] See field notes for map summarizing 1800/900 samples to date.. NOTEBY J. Longino, NOTEDATE 27-Jul-96: Glamyromyrmex: no more in alc. Trichoscapa alberti: more in alc.

meta.specimennotes: Note by J. Longino, 18-Nov-1991: Series with workers and multiple dealate queens suggests polygynous colony. Abundant erect pilosity on scapes, sides of head, mesosoma, petiole, AT3. Color uniformly red brown. Workers differ from ramulorum only in color. They are same color as queen, rather than being bicolored.
